{{redirect|Hewa|the language|Hewa language}} {{Infobox ethnic group |group = Hewa |population = 2,000 |region1 = {{flag|Papua New Guinea}} |pop1 = 2,000 |ref1 = {{lower|<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EQt1hfB2zPQC&pg=PA144&lpg=PP1 |title=Landscape, Process and Power |author=Heckler |page=144 | isbn=978-1-84545-549-1 | date=2009-05-30}}</ref>}} |languages = |religions = |related = |footnotes = }}
The '''Hewa''' are an [[indigenous people]] that live in the Koroba Lake Kopiago Electorate of [[Hela Province]] of [[Papua New Guinea]] near the junction of the [[Strickland River|Strickland]] River.They were one of the last peoples in Papua New Guinea to come into contact with the outside world. They number about 2,000 persons, and their rugged [[rainforest]] terrain comprises about {{convert|200|sqmi|0}},<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=EQt1hfB2zPQC&pg=PA144&lpg=PP1&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html Landscape, Process and Power by Heckler et al, page 144]</ref> some of which was unexplored until 2008.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/gallery/2009/mar/25/papua-new-guinea-new-species?picture=345036498 Guardian article about new species in New Guinea]</ref> [[Hewa language|Their language]] belongs to the Sepik family.
They hunt birds, reptiles and mammals for food, adornment and trade with neighboring tribes.<ref name="GeoPlanning">[http://geographyplanning.buffalostate.edu/MSG%202002/10_Thomas.pdf ''Back to the Future'' by Thomas, page 87]</ref> Having learned that fruit- and nectar-eating birds, such as [[fruit-dove]]s and [[lorikeet]]s, are vital to forest regeneration, the Hewa slash small gardens out of the dense jungle and allow about 20 – 25 years for the tilled yet unseeded land to be [[reforestation|reforested]] naturally.<ref name="GeoPlanning"/> Their language is not related to any outside the general area<ref>[http://www.sil.org/pacific/png/pubs/20131/4_Hewa%20Phonemes_Paul%20W%20Vollrath.pdf P. Vollrath, ''Hewa Phonemes: A Tentative Statement'']</ref> and their culture is unlike that of the other Southern Highlands tribes.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=PwQ4AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA13&dq=Hewa+%22New+Guinea%22&lr=&as_brr=3&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html ''Highland Peoples of New Guinea'' by Paula Brown, page 13]</ref> They have some limited trade with those neighboring tribes, exchanging the Hewa's animal skins, spears and nose rings for shells and boars.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=yFdbM2p8R2UC&pg=PA8&vq=Hewa&dq=Hewa+kopiago&as_brr=3&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html&source=gbs_search_r&cad=1 ''Papuan Borderlands'' by Aletta Biersack, page 8]</ref> They make paintings on flat sheets of bark but these paintings, done for magical purposes, are never traded or exhibited.<ref>Gascoigne, ''Papua New Guinea'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZIlsyGca9DoC&pg=PA100&dq=%22Hewa+people%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=5C0vU8izC6jL2QXY04DoAw&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q=%22Hewa%20people%22&f=false page 100]</ref>
They are one of the few tribes in the fringe highland area never to have practised cannibalism,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=GOeRwVWw9t4C&pg=PA131&dq=Hewa+witches&as_brr=3&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html ''Death and the Regeneration of Life'' by M. Bloch page 131 note 8]</ref> perhaps because their belief associates cannibalism with dangerous sorcerers.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=X7kn904Mzn4C&pg=PA71&dq=Hewa+witches&as_brr=3&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html ''Humors and Substances by P.J. Stewart, page 71]</ref> It is not uncommon for women accused of witchcraft to be killed.<ref>Stewart, ''Witchcraft, Sorcery, Rumors and Gossip'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=GAVEwnwC9HgC&pg=PA126&dq=%22Hewa+people%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=NCwvU7jtI4OZ2QWDooHIAQ&ved=0CEwQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=%22Hewa%20people%22&f=false page 126]</ref> The Hewa have been extensively studied by anthropologists Lyle Steadman<ref>His PhD thesis "Neighbours and Killers: residence and dominance among the Hewa of New Guinea" was cited in [https://books.google.com/books?id=19DNKof9j84C&pg=PA234&dq=%22+Neighbours+and+Killers:+residence+and+dominance+among+the+Hewa+of+New+Guinea%22&as_brr=3&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html ''Stages of Thought'' by M.H. Barnes] The first chapter is available at [https://libraries.ucsd.edu/apps/public/#DOV&bb1537077vQUE&q=Steadman%20Hewa&fq=NOT+category:(bb36527497+OR+bb1093000r+OR+bb23558110+OR+component)+AND+NOT+attrib:(%22xdre this link]</ref> and William H. Thomas.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=EQt1hfB2zPQC&pg=PA144&lpg=PP1&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html Landscape, Process and Power, by Heckler et al, page 140ff]</ref> The Hewa were also featured on the final episode of the [[Discovery Channel]] program ''[[Survivorman]]'' and in a later program called ''[[Beyond Survival]]''.
The Hewa were one of the last peoples in Papua New Guinea to come into contact with the outside world. Many Hewa people north of the Lagaip River were uncontacted until 1975, when the Officer in Charge at Kopiago braved arrow attacks and led what probably was Papua New Guinea's last "first contact patrol", bringing steel axeheads to an area where stone axeheads were the norm.<ref>[http://exkiap.net/forum/viewtopic.php?f=2&t=1041&view=previous OIC Kopiago post 1]</ref><ref>[http://exkiap.net/forum/viewtopic.php?f=2&t=1184&view=next OIC Kopiago post 2]</ref> Even south of the Lagaip, many Hewa families were first contacted by Steadman in the late 1960s.<ref name="Steadman, op. cit.">Steadman, ''op. cit.''</ref> He found that the typical family (which averaged seven people) lived in relative isolation from other families, with their nearest neighbors living half a mile away through dense jungle.<ref name="Steadman, op. cit."/> After darkness envelops their isolated realm, the families often stay awake for hours, the men telling myths and stories around a fire, and the women, gathered around a separate fire in their section of the house, often interrupting with well-timed quips and jests.<ref>Brian Schwartz, ''A World of Villages'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=o_R_AAAAMAAJ&q=%22Bamiah+or+Borobuan+would+tell+a+story%22&dq=%22Bamiah+or+Borobuan+would+tell+a+story%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qbYtU_PPEvPO2QXY8IDgCA&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAA page 54-5]</ref> Sometimes, historical tales are sung or chanted.<ref>''Sung Tales from the Papua New Guinea highlands'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=DR7ZPcwRf-AC&pg=PA321&dq=%22Hewa+language%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=AygvU_PxHYGO2AXq54HYDg&ved=0CEEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Hewa&f=false page 29]</ref>
In recent decades, change has come to the region. Many Hewa wear Western clothes instead of the traditional grass skirts; though the majority still live in scattered households,<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/1420989/The_mammal_fauna_of_Wanakipa_Southern_Highlands_Province_Papua_New_Guinea ''Mammal Fauna of Wanakipa'']</ref> many now live in villages and travel agencies fly tourists to newly constructed airstrips to visit them.<ref>[http://www.goway.com/groups/groupsonly-by-goway/sample-group-itineraries/papua-new-guinea-journey-senses/ Goway Tours tour itinerary]</ref>
