{{Infobox language family |name=Saho–Afar |region=[[Eritrea]], [[Ethiopia]], [[Djibouti]] |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Cushitic languages|Cushitic]] |fam3=[[Lowland East Cushitic languages|Lowland East]] |child1=[[Afar language|Afar]] |child2=[[Saho language|Saho]] |glotto=saho1245 |glottorefname=Saho–Afar }}
The '''Saho–Afar languages''' (also known as '''Afar–Saho''') are a dialect-cluster belonging to the [[Cushitic languages|Cushitic]] branch of the [[Afroasiatic languages|Afro-Asiatic]] family. They include the [[Afar language|Afar]] and [[Saho language|Saho]] languages, which are spoken in [[Djibouti]], [[Eritrea]] and [[Ethiopia]].<ref>Raymond G. Gordon Jr., ed. 2005. ''Ethnologue: Languages of the World''. 15th edition. Dallas: Summer Institute of Linguistics.</ref>
